While the atmosphere is lively, the number of stalls is quite limited, and the layout feels a bit cramped. With better management and organization, this market could attract more visitors and even tourists, especially since it's located near the scenic Tun Teja Bridge.

One thing that would make the experience more enjoyable is the availability of properly arranged seating areas. Even something as simple as "healing chairs" could go a long way in making the space more comfortable for everyone.

However, food prices here are slightly on the higher side compared to other night markets. A bit more value for money would definitely enhance the overall appeal.

In summary, it's a decent place to visit for a casual evening out, but with some improvements in layout, facilities, and pricing, Teja Flea Night Market could become a real highlight in the Notably, the Glam Bazar Ramadan Klebang 2024 recorded over 300,000 visitors and achieved sales totaling RM3 million, surpassing initial expectations. citeturn0search0

Spanning approximately two kilometers, Bazaar Klebang is considered one of the longest bazaars in Malaysia. In 2019, it accommodated around 400 vendors across 360 stalls, offering a diverse array of products ranging from clothing and accessories to local delicacies. citeturn0search2 This extensive selection ensures that visitors can find various items to suit their preferences.

The bazaar's strategic location and ample parking facilities contribute to its accessibility and appeal. Its popularity is further evidenced by significant attendance figures, such as the 70,000 visitors reported in a single night during the 2022 Aidilfitri celebrations. citeturn0search1 Such events highlight the bazaar's role as a central hub for festive shopping and community gatherings.

Beyond shopping, Bazaar Klebang offers a lively atmosphere with various entertainment options. Visitors can enjoy fire shows at Klebang Beach on weekends and school holidays, enhancing the overall experience. The presence of a playground equipped with e-scooters, e-bikes, and traditional play equipment makes it a family-friendly destination. Additionally, nearby attractions like go-kart facilities provide further entertainment choices. citeturn0search4

[{"review_id":"ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSURLOEpqcW1RRRAB","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSURLOEpqcW1RRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x3d1772a5c689c89c!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgIDK8JjqmQE%7CCgwIvamghAYQ8LP4jAE%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"Nibbles On Mars","reviewer_id":"113103785110839287321","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/113103785110839287321?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"There is only one entrance (from the residential area) and volunteers are always present there to ensure strict adherence to SOPs -- to scan MySejahtera or register manually, to measure body temperature and to obtain a 'number card' to limit the number of visitors at the bazaar at any one time 

Food stalls only occupy one side of the road (instead of both sides) and therefore there is plenty of space for visitors to maintain physical distance. Some stall owners require their customers to queue when buying food by setting up 'taped cones' in front of their stalls. Kudos to them! However it is at your own risk to distance sufficiently from one another during the entire visit.

I recommend the Nasi Kerabu (from Nor Amiza CK) and Nasi Lemak Kampung Morten with their Ayam Rendang  There was a satay stall (Sate Penjara) selling one skewer at only RM0.50 -- a rare find nowadays! Many other stalls sell Nasi Biryani, Nasi Campur, fried chicken, kuih, roti/ murtabak and fruit juices.

One downside of this bazaar is that it always cause heavy traffic along the AMJ highway due to the many cars parked illegally along the highway right outside of Semabok Perdana. [{"review_id":"ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRZ3ZTdDFnRRAB","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRZ3ZTdDFnRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x95dbea6bd4ccfadf!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgMCQgvSt1gE%7CCgsIq8aVvgYQqPKdKQ%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"Doraemon","reviewer_id":"112665277904119154671","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/112665277904119154671?hl=en-GB","rating":3,"review_text":"Kitty and I, along with a group of friends, recently visited the Jonker Street Night Market in Melaka, Malaysia. It was a sensory overload in the best way possible. The vibrant atmosphere was infectious, with bustling crowds and the mouthwatering aroma of street food filling the air. It was like a celebration of all things delicious. We loved the cheerful contrast of bright blue awnings over the food stalls against the warm tones of the buildings and the clear blue sky. It was truly inviting.

We especially enjoyed the Jonker Food Market Street, where all the hawker stalls were gathered together. It was a feast for the eyes and the stomach. We bought a variety of dishes from different stalls, like char kway teow, smelly tofu rojak, fried mee, yakitori, and more. Our friends also tried the different types of carrot cake, white and black. They even got curry mee and a mala xiangguo. It was a real smorgasbord of flavours.

The char kway teow and carrot cake, despite their appealing looks, felt a bit bland to us. Maybe this is the way how the carrot cake and the char kway teow are cooked in Malacca. As we bought all these dishes from the different stalls, and all of them tasted the same, only one of the stalls had a better taste. However, to us, it was still quite bland. The smelly tofu was not very smelly when it was brought to the table. However, when you put it into your mouth, it was damn smelly. The smelly taste was not that kind of a flavorful taste. The smell tofu tasted like a longkang smell, like those big dirty drains choked for months, and the taste was awful. The curry mee was okay. The rojak was a bit watery and the prawn paste, the rojak prawn paste, was not flavorful either. The yakitori of two sticks of beef wasn't very nice too, and it was a bit expensive, costing RM32 for the two steaks of beef yakitori.

The dish that stood out in this hawker stall was the mala xiang guo, which was flavorful - the chicken wings were nice and nicely BBQ'd. There's also an oyster store, which we bought the fried oysters in a Thai style. The oyster was also nice and it was fresh too. The hawker stores also accept Touch & Go with cashless payment which was nice.

We were incredibly lucky to arrive early, around 5:45, just as the hawker stalls were setting up. It was great to be able to get a table for our group of nine. Usually, it's hard to find seating, especially with such a big group, but we were able to snag three tables and sit together, enjoying the early evening air.

It was so cool at that time of the day, with the sun beginning to set. But just as we were finishing our meal, the rain came! The hawker stalls quickly brought out their big, heavy awnings, but it took a little time to set them up. We had to run to a nearby shop for shelter, and our food and seats were already wet. But luckily, we were almost done with our meal.

Overall, the Jonker Street Night Market is a must-visit for anyone travelling to Melaka. It's a vibrant and exciting experience that offers a unique glimpse into local culture and cuisine. It's definitely a community-focused outdoor dining experience that captures the essence of a typical Asian night market! We recommend going early to avoid the crowds and get a good spot, but be prepared for a possible downpour. Also, be prepared for the taste to be different from what you might be used to. [{"review_id":"ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRNmVmdHNRRRAB","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnTUNRNmVmdHNRRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0xe92cdb435cbf8242!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgMCQ6eftsQE%7CCgwIrP6hvgYQ-PH36wE%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"oXRYSTALo Ong","reviewer_id":"114556064085815871377","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/114556064085815871377?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Jonker Street Fruit Tea Stall: A Refreshing Treat Amidst the Night Market Buzz (4/5 Stars)

Rating:

* Taste: 4.5/5 (Delicious and refreshing honey lemon passion fruit, perfectly balanced sweetness and tartness)

* Value: 4/5 (Very reasonable prices)

* Ambience: 4/5 (Lively and energetic, typical of a night market)

Overall: 4/5

Donkey and I were strolling through the lively night market in Jonker Street, and the aroma of fresh fruit and the vibrant colors of the fruit tea stall caught our attention.

The stall had a large menu board displaying various fruit tea combinations, all featuring delicious blends of passion fruit, lemon, honey, and other fruits. There were several cups of prepared drinks on display, and signs advertising a "Happy Hour Half Price" deal. The overall atmosphere was buzzing with energy, typical of a night market.

We decided to try the honey lemon passion fruit, which was incredibly refreshing. The combination of tartness and sweetness was perfect, and the drink definitely quenched our thirst after walking around the market. The prices were very reasonable.

If you're looking for a delicious and refreshing drink while exploring the night market in Jonker Street, we recommend checking out this fruit tea stall.","published_at":"8 months Megamall\nAddress: Jln Merdeka, Banda Hilir, 75000 Melaka\n\nDataran Pahlawan Melaka Megamall is conveniently located in the heart of Banda Hilir and offers a decent selection of local snacks and quick meals at its small food court. However, the mall lacks a large grocery store, which can be inconvenient for extended stays or those needing everyday essentials. The dining and entertainment choices are relatively modest, and finding a parking spot could be frustrating. I found quite a long lower-floor alleyway with lots of interesting booths. The mall's design leans on the plain side, lacking the modern flair and lively atmosphere of more contemporary shopping centres. That said, it still serves well for a quick visit, whether after a simple snack, a casual browse, or just a place to rest your feet while exploring the city.","published_at":"6 months I spent a few hours walking along Jonker Street, and it was a really good experience. You can truly feel the beautiful culture here. Similar to other Chinatowns, the street is filled with restaurants, cafes, and souvenir shops. It gets very crowded during peak hours, especially on weekends or school holidays, so plan your visit wisely.

At night, the atmosphere is amazing with vibrant lighting along the shops and even by the river near Jonker Street, making it extra lively and picturesque.

Jonker Street is also one of the most strategic places to explore from here, you can easily head over to Dataran Pahlawan and other historical landmarks in Melaka. Definitely worth a visit.","published_at":"a month
